      content: "Buds will sprout on the staff belonging to the man I choose. Then
        I will finally put an end to the people\u2019s murmuring and complaining
        against you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses gave the instructions to the people of Israel, and each
        of the twelve tribal leaders, including Aaron, brought Moses a staff. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses placed the staffs in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        presence in the Tabernacle of the Covenant.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '17:7 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'Tabernacle of the Testimony; '
        - ft: also in 17:8.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "When he went into the Tabernacle of the Covenant the next day, he
        found that Aaron\u2019s staff, representing the tribe of Levi, had sprouted,
        budded, blossomed, and produced ripe almonds!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Moses brought all the staffs out from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        presence, he showed them to the people. Each man claimed his own staff. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses: \u201CPlace Aaron\u2019s
        staff permanently before the Ark of the Covenant[COMMENT[0]] to serve as
        a warning to rebels. This should put an end to their complaints against me
        and prevent any further deaths.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '17:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'before the Testimony; '
        - ft: see note on 17:4.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses did as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the people of Israel said to Moses, \u201CLook, we are doomed!
        We are dead! We are ruined! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Everyone who even comes close to the Tabernacle of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        dies. Are we all doomed to die?\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Duties of Priests and Levites
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Aaron: \u201CYou, your
        sons, and your relatives from the tribe of Levi will be held responsible
        for any offenses related to the sanctuary. But you and your sons alone will
        be held responsible for violations connected with the priesthood.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBring your relatives of the tribe of Levi\u2014your ancestral
        tribe\u2014to assist you and your sons as you perform the sacred duties in
        front of the Tabernacle of the Covenant.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Tabernacle of the Testimony.
    - title: 
      content: 'But as the Levites go about all their assigned duties at the Tabernacle,
        they must be careful not to go near any of the sacred objects or the altar.
        If they do, both you and they will die. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Levites must join you in fulfilling their responsibilities for
        the care and maintenance of the Tabernacle,[COMMENT[0]] but no unauthorized
        person may assist you.  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:4 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'the Tent of Meeting; '
        - ft: also in 18:6, 21, 22, 23, 31.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou yourselves must perform the sacred duties inside the sanctuary
        and at the altar. If you follow these instructions, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        anger will never again blaze against the people of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I myself have chosen your fellow Levites from among the Israelites
        to be your special assistants. They are a gift to you, dedicated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        for service in the Tabernacle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But you and your sons, the priests, must personally handle all the
        priestly rituals associated with the altar and with everything behind the
        inner curtain. I am giving you the priesthood as your special privilege of
        service. Any unauthorized person who comes too near the sanctuary will be
        put to death.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Support for the Priests and Levites
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave these further instructions to
        Aaron: \u201CI myself have put you in charge of all the holy offerings that
        are brought to me by the people of Israel. I have given all these consecrated
        offerings to you and your sons as your permanent share. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You are allotted the portion of the most holy offerings that is not
        burned on the fire. This portion of all the most holy offerings\u2014including
        the grain offerings, sin offerings, and guilt offerings\u2014will be most
        holy, and it belongs to you and your sons. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You must eat it as a most holy offering. All the males may eat of
        it, and you must treat it as most holy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll the sacred offerings and special offerings presented to
        me when the Israelites lift them up before the altar also belong to you.
        I have given them to you and to your sons and daughters as your permanent
        share. Any member of your family who is ceremonially clean may eat of these
        offerings.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI also give you the harvest gifts brought by the people as
        offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2014the best of the olive
        oil, new wine, and grain. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the first crops of their land that the people present to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> belong to you. Any member of your family who
        is ceremonially clean may eat this food.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEverything in Israel that is specially set apart for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>[COMMENT[0]]
        also belongs to you.  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of things
            or people to the '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe firstborn of every mother, whether human or animal, that
        is offered to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will be yours. But you must
        always redeem your firstborn sons and the firstborn of ceremonially unclean
        animals. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Redeem them when they are one month old. The redemption price is
        five pieces of silver[COMMENT[0]] (as measured by the weight of the sanctuary
        shekel, which equals twenty gerahs).  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '5 shekels '
        - ft: '[2 ounces or 57 grams] '
          body: of silver.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHowever, you may not redeem the firstborn of cattle, sheep,
        or goats. They are holy and have been set apart for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.
        Sprinkle their blood on the altar, and burn their fat as a special gift,
        a pleasing aroma to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The meat of these animals will be yours, just like the breast and
        right thigh that are presented by lifting them up as a special offering before
        the altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yes, I am giving you all these holy offerings that the people of
        Israel bring to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. They are for you and
        your sons and daughters, to be eaten as your permanent share. This is an
        eternal and unbreakable covenant[COMMENT[0]] between the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and you, and it also applies to your descendants.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:19 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: a covenant of salt.
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Aaron, \u201CYou priests
        will receive no allotment of land or share of property among the people of
        Israel. I am your share and your allotment. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As for the tribe of Levi, your relatives, I will compensate them
        for their service in the Tabernacle. Instead of an allotment of land, I will
        give them the tithes from the entire land of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFrom now on, no Israelites except priests or Levites may approach
        the Tabernacle. If they come too near, they will be judged guilty and will
        die. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Only the Levites may serve at the Tabernacle, and they will be held
        responsible for any offenses against it. This is a permanent law for you,
        to be observed from generation to generation. The Levites will receive no
        allotment of land among the Israelites, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "because I have given them the Israelites\u2019 tithes, which have
        been presented as sacred offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.
        This will be the Levites\u2019 share. That is why I said they would receive
        no allotment of land among the Israelites.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> also told Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGive these instructions to the Levites: When you receive from
        the people of Israel the tithes I have assigned as your allotment, give a
        tenth of the tithes you receive\u2014a tithe of the tithe\u2014to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        as a sacred offering. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will consider this offering to be
        your harvest offering, as though it were the first grain from your own threshing
        floor or wine from your own winepress. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You must present one-tenth of the tithe received from the Israelites
        as a sacred offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. This is the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s sacred portion, and you must present
        it to Aaron the priest. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Be sure to give to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> the best portions
        of the gifts given to you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAlso, give these instructions to the Levites: When you present
        the best part as your offering, it will be considered as though it came from
        your own threshing floor or winepress. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You Levites and your families may eat this food anywhere you wish,
        for it is your compensation for serving in the Tabernacle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will not be considered guilty for accepting the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        tithes if you give the best portion to the priests. But be careful not to
        treat the holy gifts of the people of Israel as though they were common.
        If you do, you will die.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Water of Purification
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses and Aaron, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHere is another legal requirement commanded by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t:
        Tell the people of Israel to bring you a red heifer, a perfect animal that
        has no defects and has never been yoked to a plow. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Give it to Eleazar the priest, and it will be taken outside the camp
        and slaughtered in his presence. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eleazar will take some of its blood on his finger and sprinkle it
        seven times toward the front of the Tabernacle.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '19:4 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the Tent of Meeting.
    - title: 
      content: "As Eleazar watches, the heifer must be burned\u2014its hide, meat,
        blood, and dung. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eleazar the priest must then take a stick of cedar,[COMMENT[0]] a
        hyssop branch, and some scarlet yarn and throw them into the fire where the
        heifer is burning.  '
      comments:
      - number: '19:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: juniper.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen the priest must wash his clothes and bathe himself in
        water. Afterward he may return to the camp, though he will remain ceremonially
        unclean until evening. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The man who burns the animal must also wash his clothes and bathe
        himself in water, and he, too, will remain unclean until evening. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then someone who is ceremonially clean will gather up the ashes of
        the heifer and deposit them in a purified place outside the camp. They will
        be kept there for the community of Israel to use in the water for the purification
        ceremony. This ceremony is performed for the removal of sin. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The man who gathers up the ashes of the heifer must also wash his
        clothes, and he will remain ceremonially unclean until evening. This is a
        permanent law for the people of Israel and any foreigners who live among
        them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll those who touch a dead human body will be ceremonially
        unclean for seven days. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They must purify themselves on the third and seventh days with the
        water of purification; then they will be purified. But if they do not do
        this on the third and seventh days, they will continue to be unclean even
        after the seventh day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All those who touch a dead body and do not purify themselves in the
        proper way defile the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s Tabernacle,
        and they will be cut off from the community of Israel. Since the water of
        purification was not sprinkled on them, their defilement continues.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is the ritual law that applies when someone dies inside
        a tent: All those who enter that tent and those who were inside when the
        death occurred will be ceremonially unclean for seven days. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Any open container in the tent that was not covered with a lid is
        also defiled. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And if someone in an open field touches the corpse of someone who
        was killed with a sword or who died a natural death, or if someone touches
        a human bone or a grave, that person will be defiled for seven days.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTo remove the defilement, put some of the ashes from the burnt
        purification offering in a jar, and pour fresh water over them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then someone who is ceremonially clean must take a hyssop branch
        and dip it into the water. That person must sprinkle the water on the tent,
        on all the furnishings in the tent, and on the people who were in the tent;
        also on the person who touched a human bone, or touched someone who was killed
        or who died naturally, or touched a grave. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the third and seventh days the person who is ceremonially clean
        must sprinkle the water on those who are defiled. Then on the seventh day
        the people being cleansed must wash their clothes and bathe themselves, and
        that evening they will be cleansed of their defilement.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut those who become defiled and do not purify themselves will
        be cut off from the community, for they have defiled the sanctuary of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. Since the water of purification has not
        been sprinkled on them, they remain defiled. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is a permanent law for the people. Those who sprinkle the water
        of purification must afterward wash their clothes, and anyone who then touches
        the water used for purification will remain defiled until evening. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Anything and anyone that a defiled person touches will be ceremonially
        unclean until evening.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Moses Strikes the Rock
      content: 'In the first month of the year,[COMMENT[0]] the whole community of
        Israel arrived in the wilderness of Zin and camped at Kadesh. While they
        were there, Miriam died and was buried.  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: The first month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs
            within the months of March and April. The number of years since leaving
            Egypt is not specified.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'There was no water for the people to drink at that place, so they
        rebelled against Moses and Aaron. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people blamed Moses and said, \u201CIf only we had died in the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s presence with our brothers! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why have you brought the congregation of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        people into this wilderness to die, along with all our livestock? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why did you make us leave Egypt and bring us here to this terrible
        place? This land has no grain, no figs, no grapes, no pomegranates, and no
        water to drink!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses and Aaron turned away from the people and went to the entrance
        of the Tabernacle,[COMMENT[0]] where they fell face down on the ground. Then
        the glorious presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared to them, '
      comments:
      - number: '20:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the Tent of Meeting.
    - title: 
      content: 'and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou and Aaron must take the staff and assemble the entire community.
        As the people watch, speak to the rock over there, and it will pour out its
        water. You will provide enough water from the rock to satisfy the whole community
        and their livestock.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses did as he was told. He took the staff from the place where
        it was kept before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he and Aaron summoned the people to come and gather at the rock.
        \u201CListen, you rebels!\u201D he shouted. \u201CMust we bring you water
        from this rock?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Moses raised his hand and struck the rock twice with the staff,
        and water gushed out. So the entire community and their livestock drank their
        fill.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses and Aaron, \u201CBecause
        you did not trust me enough to demonstrate my holiness to the people of Israel,
        you will not lead them into the land I am giving them!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This place was known as the waters of Meribah (which means \u201Carguing\u201D)
        because there the people of Israel argued with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t,
        and there he demonstrated his holiness among them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Edom Refuses Israel Passage
      content: "While Moses was at Kadesh, he sent ambassadors to the king of Edom
        with this message:\n\t\u201CThis is what your relatives, the people of Israel,
        say: You know all the hardships we have been through. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Our ancestors went down to Egypt, and we lived there a long time,
        and we and our ancestors were brutally mistreated by the Egyptians. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when we cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, he
        heard us and sent an angel who brought us out of Egypt. Now we are camped
        at Kadesh, a town on the border of your land. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Please let us travel through your land. We will be careful not to
        go through your fields and vineyards. We won\u2019t even drink water from
        your wells. We will stay on the king\u2019s road and never leave it until
        we have passed through your territory.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the king of Edom said, \u201CStay out of my land, or I will meet
        you with an army!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Israelites answered, \u201CWe will stay on the main road. If
        our livestock drink your water, we will pay for it. Just let us pass through
        your country. That\u2019s all we ask.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the king of Edom replied, \u201CStay out! You may not pass through
        our land.\u201D With that he mobilized his army and marched out against them
        with an imposing force. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Because Edom refused to allow Israel to pass through their country,
        Israel was forced to turn around.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Death of Aaron
      content: 'The whole community of Israel left Kadesh and arrived at Mount Hor. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There, on the border of the land of Edom, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said to Moses and Aaron, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe time has come for Aaron to join his ancestors in death.
        He will not enter the land I am giving the people of Israel, because the
        two of you rebelled against my instructions concerning the water at Meribah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now take Aaron and his son Eleazar up Mount Hor. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "There you will remove Aaron\u2019s priestly garments and put them
        on Eleazar, his son. Aaron will die there and join his ancestors.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses did as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded. The three
        of them went up Mount Hor together as the whole community watched. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At the summit, Moses removed the priestly garments from Aaron and
        put them on Eleazar, Aaron\u2019s son. Then Aaron died there on top of the
        mountain, and Moses and Eleazar went back down. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: When the people realized that Aaron had died, all Israel mourned for
        him thirty days.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Victory over the Canaanites
      content: 'The Canaanite king of Arad, who lived in the Negev, heard that the
        Israelites were approaching on the road through Atharim. So he attacked the
        Israelites and took some of them as prisoners. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the people of Israel made this vow to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t:
        \u201CIf you will hand these people over to us, we will completely destroy[COMMENT[0]]
        all their towns.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '21:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of things
            or people to the '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> heard the Israelites\u2019 request
        and gave them victory over the Canaanites. The Israelites completely destroyed
        them and their towns, and the place has been called Hormah[COMMENT[0]] ever
        since.  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:3 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Hormah '
        - ft: "means \u201Cdestruction.\u201D"
          body: 
    - title: The Bronze Snake
      content: 'Then the people of Israel set out from Mount Hor, taking the road
        to the Red Sea[COMMENT[0]] to go around the land of Edom. But the people
        grew impatient with the long journey, '
      comments:
      - number: '21:4 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: sea of reeds.
    - title: 
      content: "and they began to speak against God and Moses. \u201CWhy have you
        brought us out of Egypt to die here in the wilderness?\u201D they complained.
        \u201CThere is nothing to eat here and nothing to drink. And we hate this
        horrible manna!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent poisonous snakes among the
        people, and many were bitten and died. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the people came to Moses and cried out, \u201CWe have sinned
        by speaking against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and against you. Pray
        that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will take away the snakes.\u201D So
        Moses prayed for the people.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him, \u201CMake a replica
        of a poisonous snake and attach it to a pole. All who are bitten will live
        if they simply look at it!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses made a snake out of bronze and attached it to a pole. Then
        anyone who was bitten by a snake could look at the bronze snake and be healed!  '
      comments: []
    - title: "Israel\u2019s Journey to Moab"
      content: 'The Israelites traveled next to Oboth and camped there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they went on to Iye-abarim, in the wilderness on the eastern
        border of Moab. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From there they traveled to the valley of Zered Brook and set up
        camp. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they moved out and camped on the far side of the Arnon River,
        in the wilderness adjacent to the territory of the Amorites. The Arnon is
        the boundary line between the Moabites and the Amorites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For this reason \n\tThe Book of the Wars of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        speaks of \u201Cthe town of Waheb in the area of Suphah, and the ravines
        of the Arnon River, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and the ravines that extend as far as the settlement of Ar on the
        border of Moab.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "From there the Israelites traveled to Beer,[COMMENT[0]] which is
        the well where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CAssemble
        the people, and I will give them water.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '21:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Beer '
        - ft: "means \u201Cwell.\u201D"
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "There the Israelites sang this song:\n\t\u201CSpring up, O well!\n\tYes,
        sing its praises!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Sing of this well,\n\twhich princes dug,\n\twhich great leaders hollowed
        out\n\twith their scepters and staffs.\u201D\n\tThen the Israelites left
        the wilderness and proceeded on through Mattanah, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nahaliel, and Bamoth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After that they went to the valley in Moab where Pisgah Peak overlooks
        the wasteland.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:20 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: overlooks Jeshimon.
    - title: Victory over Sihon and Og
      content: 'The Israelites sent ambassadors to King Sihon of the Amorites with
        this message:  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLet us travel through your land. We will be careful not to
        go through your fields and vineyards. We won\u2019t even drink water from
        your wells. We will stay on the king\u2019s road until we have passed through
        your territory.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But King Sihon refused to let them cross his territory. Instead,
        he mobilized his entire army and attacked Israel in the wilderness, engaging
        them in battle at Jahaz. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the Israelites slaughtered them with their swords and occupied
        their land from the Arnon River to the Jabbok River. They went only as far
        as the Ammonite border because the boundary of the Ammonites was fortified.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:24 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'because the terrain of the Ammonite frontier was rugged; '
        - ft: 'Hebrew reads '
          body: because the boundary of the Ammonites was strong.
    - title: 
      content: 'So Israel captured all the towns of the Amorites and settled in them,
        including the city of Heshbon and its surrounding villages. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Heshbon had been the capital of King Sihon of the Amorites. He had
        defeated a former Moabite king and seized all his land as far as the Arnon
        River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Therefore, the ancient poets wrote this about him:\n\t\u201CCome
        to Heshbon and let it be rebuilt!\n\tLet the city of Sihon be restored.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A fire flamed forth from Heshbon,\n\ta blaze from the city of Sihon.\n\tIt
        burned the city of Ar in Moab;\n\tit destroyed the rulers of the Arnon heights.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What sorrow awaits you, O people of Moab!\n\tYou are finished, O
        worshipers of Chemosh!\n\tChemosh has left his sons as refugees,\n\this daughters
        as captives of Sihon, the Amorite king.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We have utterly destroyed them,\n\tfrom Heshbon to Dibon.\n\tWe have
        completely wiped them out\n\tas far away as Nophah and Medeba.[COMMENT[0]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:30 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'until fire spread to Medeba. '
        - ft: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'So the people of Israel occupied the territory of the Amorites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After Moses sent men to explore the Jazer area, they captured all
        the towns in the region and drove out the Amorites who lived there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they turned and marched up the road to Bashan, but King Og of
        Bashan and all his people attacked them at Edrei. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CDo not be afraid
        of him, for I have handed him over to you, along with all his people and
        his land. Do the same to him as you did to King Sihon of the Amorites, who
        ruled in Heshbon.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: And Israel killed King Og, his sons, and all his subjects; not a single
        survivor remained. Then Israel occupied their land.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Balak Sends for Balaam
      content: 'Then the people of Israel traveled to the plains of Moab and camped
        east of the Jordan River, across from Jericho. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Balak son of Zippor, the Moabite king, had seen everything the Israelites
        did to the Amorites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And when the people of Moab saw how many Israelites there were, they
        were terrified. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king of Moab said to the elders of Midian, \u201CThis mob will
        devour everything in sight, like an ox devours grass in the field!\u201D\n\tSo
        Balak, king of Moab, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "sent messengers to call Balaam son of Beor, who was living in his
        native land of Pethor[COMMENT[0]] near the Euphrates River.[COMMENT[1]] His
        message said:\n\t\u201CLook, a vast horde of people has arrived from Egypt.
        They cover the face of the earth and are threatening me. "
      comments:
      - number: '22:5a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: who was at Pethor in the land of the Amavites.
      - number: '22:5b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the river.
    - title: 
      content: "Please come and curse these people for me because they are too powerful
        for me. Then perhaps I will be able to conquer them and drive them from the
        land. I know that blessings fall on any people you bless, and curses fall
        on people you curse.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Balak\u2019s messengers, who were elders of Moab and Midian, set
        out with money to pay Balaam to place a curse upon Israel.[COMMENT[0]] They
        went to Balaam and delivered Balak\u2019s message to him. "
      comments:
      - number: '22:7 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: set out with the money of divination in their hand.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CStay here overnight,\u201D Balaam said. \u201CIn the morning
        I will tell you whatever the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> directs me to say.\u201D
        So the officials from Moab stayed there with Balaam.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "That night God came to Balaam and asked him, \u201CWho are these
        men visiting you?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Balaam said to God, \u201CBalak son of Zippor, king of Moab, has
        sent me this message: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Look, a vast horde of people has arrived from Egypt, and they
        cover the face of the earth. Come and curse these people for me. Then perhaps
        I will be able to stand up to them and drive them from the land.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But God told Balaam, \u201CDo not go with them. You are not to curse
        these people, for they have been blessed!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The next morning Balaam got up and told Balak\u2019s officials, \u201CGo
        on home! The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will not let me go with you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the Moabite officials returned to King Balak and reported, \u201CBalaam
        refused to come with us.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Balak tried again. This time he sent a larger number of even
        more distinguished officials than those he had sent the first time. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They went to Balaam and delivered this message to him:\n\t\u201CThis
        is what Balak son of Zippor says: Please don\u2019t let anything stop you
        from coming to help me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will pay you very well and do whatever you tell me. Just come and
        curse these people for me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Balaam responded to Balak\u2019s messengers, \u201CEven if Balak
        were to give me his palace filled with silver and gold, I would be powerless
        to do anything against the will of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> my God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But stay here one more night, and I will see if the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has anything else to say to me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "That night God came to Balaam and told him, \u201CSince these men
        have come for you, get up and go with them. But do only what I tell you to
        do.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Balaam and His Donkey
      content: 'So the next morning Balaam got up, saddled his donkey, and started
        off with the Moabite officials. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But God was angry that Balaam was going, so he sent the angel of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to stand in the road to block his way. As
        Balaam and two servants were riding along, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Balaam\u2019s donkey saw the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        standing in the road with a drawn sword in his hand. The donkey bolted off
        the road into a field, but Balaam beat it and turned it back onto the road. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> stood at a place
        where the road narrowed between two vineyard walls. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the donkey saw the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t,
        it tried to squeeze by and crushed Balaam\u2019s foot against the wall. So
        Balaam beat the donkey again. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> moved farther down
        the road and stood in a place too narrow for the donkey to get by at all. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This time when the donkey saw the angel, it lay down under Balaam.
        In a fit of rage Balaam beat the animal again with his staff.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave the donkey the ability
        to speak. \u201CWhat have I done to you that deserves your beating me three
        times?\u201D it asked Balaam.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou have made me look like a fool!\u201D Balaam shouted. \u201CIf
        I had a sword with me, I would kill you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut I am the same donkey you have ridden all your life,\u201D
        the donkey answered. \u201CHave I ever done anything like this before?\u201D\n\t\u201CNo,\u201D
        Balaam admitted.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> opened Balaam\u2019s eyes, and
        he saw the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> standing in the roadway
        with a drawn sword in his hand. Balaam bowed his head and fell face down
        on the ground before him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy did you beat your donkey those three times?\u201D the angel
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> demanded. \u201CLook, I have come to block
        your way because you are stubbornly resisting me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Three times the donkey saw me and shied away; otherwise, I would
        certainly have killed you by now and spared the donkey.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Balaam confessed to the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t,
        \u201CI have sinned. I didn\u2019t realize you were standing in the road
        to block my way. I will return home if you are against my going.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Balaam, \u201CGo
        with these men, but say only what I tell you to say.\u201D So Balaam went
        on with Balak\u2019s officials. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When King Balak heard that Balaam was on the way, he went out to
        meet him at a Moabite town on the Arnon River at the farthest border of his
        land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDidn\u2019t I send you an urgent invitation? Why didn\u2019t
        you come right away?\u201D Balak asked Balaam. \u201CDidn\u2019t you believe
        me when I said I would reward you richly?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Balaam replied, \u201CLook, now I have come, but I have no power
        to say whatever I want. I will speak only the message that God puts in my
        mouth.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Balaam accompanied Balak to Kiriath-huzoth, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'where the king sacrificed cattle and sheep. He sent portions of the
        meat to Balaam and the officials who were with him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: The next morning Balak took Balaam up to Bamoth-baal. From there he
        could see some of the people of Israel spread out below him.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Balaam Blesses Israel
      content: "Then Balaam said to King Balak, \u201CBuild me seven altars here,
        and prepare seven young bulls and seven rams for me to sacrifice.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Balak followed his instructions, and the two of them sacrificed a
        young bull and a ram on each altar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Balaam said to Balak, \u201CStand here by your burnt offerings,
        and I will go to see if the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will respond to me.
        Then I will tell you whatever he reveals to me.\u201D So Balaam went alone
        to the top of a bare hill, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and God met him there. Balaam said to him, \u201CI have prepared
        seven altars and have sacrificed a young bull and a ram on each altar.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave Balaam a message for King Balak.
        Then he said, \u201CGo back to Balak and give him my message.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Balaam returned and found the king standing beside his burnt offerings
        with all the officials of Moab. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This was the message Balaam delivered:\n\t\u201CBalak summoned me
        to come from Aram;\n\tthe king of Moab brought me from the eastern hills.\n\t\u2018Come,\u2019
        he said, \u2018curse Jacob for me!\n\tCome and announce Israel\u2019s doom.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But how can I curse those\n\twhom God has not cursed?\n\tHow can
        I condemn those\n\twhom the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has not condemned?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I see them from the cliff tops;\n\tI watch them from the hills.\n\tI
        see a people who live by themselves,\n\tset apart from other nations.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Who can count Jacob\u2019s descendants, as numerous as dust?\n\tWho
        can count even a fourth of Israel\u2019s people?\n\tLet me die like the righteous;\n\tlet
        my life end like theirs.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then King Balak demanded of Balaam, \u201CWhat have you done to me?
        I brought you to curse my enemies. Instead, you have blessed them!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Balaam replied, \u201CI will speak only the message that the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> puts in my mouth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Balaam\u2019s Second Message"
      content: "Then King Balak told him, \u201CCome with me to another place. There
        you will see another part of the nation of Israel, but not all of them. Curse
        at least that many!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Balak took Balaam to the plateau of Zophim on Pisgah Peak. He
        built seven altars there and offered a young bull and a ram on each altar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Balaam said to the king, \u201CStand here by your burnt offerings
        while I go over there to meet the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> met Balaam and gave him a message.
        Then he said, \u201CGo back to Balak and give him my message.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Balaam returned and found the king standing beside his burnt offerings
        with all the officials of Moab. \u201CWhat did the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        say?\u201D Balak asked eagerly.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This was the message Balaam delivered:\n\t\u201CRise up, Balak, and
        listen!\n\tHear me, son of Zippor.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God is not a man, so he does not lie.\n\tHe is not human, so he does
        not change his mind.\n\tHas he ever spoken and failed to act?\n\tHas he ever
        promised and not carried it through?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Listen, I received a command to bless;\n\tGod has blessed, and I
        cannot reverse it!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No misfortune is in his plan for Jacob;\n\tno trouble is in store
        for Israel.\n\tFor the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God is with them;\n\the
        has been proclaimed their king.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God brought them out of Egypt;\n\tfor them he is as strong as a wild
        ox.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No curse can touch Jacob;\n\tno magic has any power against Israel.\n\tFor
        now it will be said of Jacob,\n\t\u2018What wonders God has done for Israel!\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These people rise up like a lioness,\n\tlike a majestic lion rousing
        itself.\n\tThey refuse to rest\n\tuntil they have feasted on prey,\n\tdrinking
        the blood of the slaughtered!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Balak said to Balaam, \u201CFine, but if you won\u2019t curse
        them, at least don\u2019t bless them!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Balaam replied to Balak, \u201CDidn\u2019t I tell you that I
        can do only what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> tells me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Balaam\u2019s Third Message"
      content: "Then King Balak said to Balaam, \u201CCome, I will take you to one
        more place. Perhaps it will please God to let you curse them from there.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Balak took Balaam to the top of Mount Peor, overlooking the wasteland.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:28 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: overlooking Jeshimon.
    - title: 
      content: "Balaam again told Balak, \u201CBuild me seven altars, and prepare
        seven young bulls and seven rams for me to sacrifice.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: So Balak did as Balaam ordered and offered a young bull and a ram
        on each altar.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: 'By now Balaam realized that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was determined
        to bless Israel, so he did not resort to divination as before. Instead, he
        turned and looked out toward the wilderness, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'where he saw the people of Israel camped, tribe by tribe. Then the
        Spirit of God came upon him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and this is the message he delivered:\n\t\u201CThis is the message
        of Balaam son of Beor,\n\tthe message of the man whose eyes see clearly,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the message of one who hears the words of God,\n\twho sees a vision
        from the Almighty,\n\twho bows down with eyes wide open:  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "How beautiful are your tents, O Jacob;\n\thow lovely are your homes,
        O Israel!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They spread before me like palm groves,[COMMENT[0]]like gardens by
        the riverside.\n\tThey are like tall trees planted by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t,\n\tlike
        cedars beside the waters.  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: like a majestic valley.
    - title: 
      content: "Water will flow from their buckets;\n\ttheir offspring have all they
        need.\n\tTheir king will be greater than Agag;\n\ttheir kingdom will be exalted.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God brought them out of Egypt;\n\tfor them he is as strong as a wild
        ox.\n\tHe devours all the nations that oppose him,\n\tbreaking their bones
        in pieces,\n\tshooting them with arrows.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Like a lion, Israel crouches and lies down;\n\tlike a lioness, who
        dares to arouse her?\n\tBlessed is everyone who blesses you, O Israel,\n\tand
        cursed is everyone who curses you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "King Balak flew into a rage against Balaam. He angrily clapped his
        hands and shouted, \u201CI called you to curse my enemies! Instead, you have
        blessed them three times. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now get out of here! Go back home! I promised to reward you richly,
        but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has kept you from your reward.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Balaam told Balak, \u201CDon\u2019t you remember what I told your
        messengers? I said, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Even if Balak were to give me his palace filled with silver
        and gold, I would be powerless to do anything against the will of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.\u2019
        I told you that I could say only what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now I am returning to my own people. But first let me tell you what
        the Israelites will do to your people in the future.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Balaam\u2019s Final Messages"
      content: "This is the message Balaam delivered:\n\t\u201CThis is the message
        of Balaam son of Beor,\n\tthe message of the man whose eyes see clearly,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the message of one who hears the words of God,\n\twho has knowledge
        from the Most High,\n\twho sees a vision from the Almighty,\n\twho bows down
        with eyes wide open:  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I see him, but not here and now.\n\tI perceive him, but far in the
        distant future.\n\tA star will rise from Jacob;\n\ta scepter will emerge
        from Israel.\n\tIt will crush the heads of Moab\u2019s people,\n\tcracking
        the skulls[COMMENT[0]] of the people of Sheth.  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:17 '
        contents:
        - ft: As in Samaritan Pentateuch; the meaning of the Hebrew word is uncertain.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Edom will be taken over,\n\tand Seir, its enemy, will be conquered,\n\twhile
        Israel marches on in triumph.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A ruler will rise in Jacob\n\twho will destroy the survivors of Ir.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Balaam looked over toward the people of Amalek and delivered
        this message:\n\t\u201CAmalek was the greatest of nations,\n\tbut its destiny
        is destruction!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he looked over toward the Kenites and delivered this message:\n\t\u201CYour
        home is secure;\n\tyour nest is set in the rocks.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the Kenites will be destroyed\n\twhen Assyria[COMMENT[0]] takes
        you captive.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'Asshur; '
        - ft: also in 24:24.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Balaam concluded his messages by saying:\n\t\u201CAlas, who can survive\n\tunless
        God has willed it?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Ships will come from the coasts of Cyprus[COMMENT[0]];\n\tthey will
        oppress Assyria and afflict Eber,\n\tbut they, too, will be utterly destroyed.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:24 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: Kittim.
    - title: 
      content: Then Balaam left and returned home, and Balak also went on his way.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Moab Seduces Israel
      content: 'While the Israelites were camped at Acacia Grove,[COMMENT[0]] some
        of the men defiled themselves by having[COMMENT[1]] sexual relations with
        local Moabite women. '
      comments:
      - number: '25:1a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: Shittim.
      - number: '25:1b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Greek version; Hebrew reads '
          body: some of the men began having.
    - title: 
      content: 'These women invited them to attend sacrifices to their gods, so the
        Israelites feasted with them and worshiped the gods of Moab. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In this way, Israel joined in the worship of Baal of Peor, causing
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s anger to blaze against his people.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> issued the following command to Moses:
        \u201CSeize all the ringleaders and execute them before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        in broad daylight, so his fierce anger will turn away from the people of
        Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses ordered Israel\u2019s judges, \u201CEach of you must put
        to death the men under your authority who have joined in worshiping Baal
        of Peor.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Just then one of the Israelite men brought a Midianite woman into
        his tent, right before the eyes of Moses and all the people, as everyone
        was weeping at the entrance of the Tabernacle.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the Tent of Meeting.
    - title: 
      content: 'When Phinehas son of Eleazar and grandson of Aaron the priest saw
        this, he jumped up and left the assembly. He took a spear '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and rushed after the man into his tent. Phinehas thrust the spear
        all the way through the man\u2019s body and into the woman\u2019s stomach.
        So the plague against the Israelites was stopped, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'but not before 24,000 people had died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPhinehas son of Eleazar and grandson of Aaron the priest has
        turned my anger away from the Israelites by being as zealous among them as
        I was. So I stopped destroying all Israel as I had intended to do in my zealous
        anger. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now tell him that I am making my special covenant of peace with him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In this covenant, I give him and his descendants a permanent right
        to the priesthood, for in his zeal for me, his God, he purified the people
        of Israel, making them right with me.[COMMENT[0]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: he made atonement for the people of Israel.
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelite man killed with the Midianite woman was named Zimri
        son of Salu, the leader of a family from the tribe of Simeon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The woman\u2019s name was Cozbi; she was the daughter of Zur, the
        leader of a Midianite clan.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAttack the Midianites and destroy them, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "because they assaulted you with deceit and tricked you into worshiping
        Baal of Peor, and because of Cozbi, the daughter of a Midianite leader, who
        was killed at the time of the plague because of what happened at Peor.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "The Second Registration of Israel\u2019s Troops"
      content: 'After the plague had ended,[COMMENT[0]] the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said to Moses and to Eleazar son of Aaron the priest, '
      comments:
      - number: '26:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: The initial phrase in verse 26:1 is numbered 25:19 in Hebrew text.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFrom the whole community of Israel, record the names of all
        the warriors by their families. List all the men twenty years old or older
        who are able to go to war.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So there on the plains of Moab beside the Jordan River, across from
        Jericho, Moses and Eleazar the priest issued these instructions to the leaders
        of Israel: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CList all the men of Israel twenty years old and older, just
        as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded Moses.\u201D\n\tThis is the
        record of all the descendants of Israel who came out of Egypt.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Reuben
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Reuben, Jacob\u2019s[COMMENT[0]]
        oldest son:\n\tThe Hanochite clan, named after their ancestor Hanoch.\n\tThe
        Palluite clan, named after their ancestor Pallu.  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:5 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: "Israel\u2019s; "
        - ft: see note on 1:20-21b.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "The Hezronite clan, named after their ancestor Hezron.\n\tThe Carmite
        clan, named after their ancestor Carmi.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Reuben. Their registered troops numbered
        43,730.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pallu was the ancestor of Eliab, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and Eliab was the father of Nemuel, Dathan, and Abiram. This Dathan
        and Abiram are the same community leaders who conspired with Korah against
        Moses and Aaron, rebelling against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the earth opened up its mouth and swallowed them with Korah,
        and fire devoured 250 of their followers. This served as a warning to the
        entire nation of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'However, the sons of Korah did not die that day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Simeon
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Simeon:\n\tThe Jemuelite
        clan, named after their ancestor Jemuel.[COMMENT[0]]The Jaminite clan, named
        after their ancestor Jamin.\n\tThe Jakinite clan, named after their ancestor
        Jakin.  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Syriac version (see also Gen 46:10; Exod 6:15); Hebrew reads '
          body: Nemuelite . . . Nemuel.
    - title: 
      content: 'The Zoharite clan, named after their ancestor Zohar.[COMMENT[0]]The
        Shaulite clan, named after their ancestor Shaul.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in parallel texts at Gen 46:10 and Exod 6:15; Hebrew reads '
          body: Zerahite . . . Zerah.
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Simeon. Their registered troops numbered
        22,200.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Gad
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Gad:\n\tThe Zephonite
        clan, named after their ancestor Zephon.\n\tThe Haggite clan, named after
        their ancestor Haggi.\n\tThe Shunite clan, named after their ancestor Shuni.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Oznite clan, named after their ancestor Ozni.\n\tThe Erite clan,
        named after their ancestor Eri.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Arodite clan, named after their ancestor Arodi.[COMMENT[0]]The
        Arelite clan, named after their ancestor Areli.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:17 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Samaritan Pentateuch and Greek and Syriac versions (see also
            Gen 46:16); Hebrew reads '
          body: Arod.
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Gad. Their registered troops numbered 40,500.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Judah
      content: 'Judah had two sons, Er and Onan, who had died in the land of Canaan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the clans descended from Judah\u2019s surviving sons:\n\tThe
        Shelanite clan, named after their ancestor Shelah.\n\tThe Perezite clan,
        named after their ancestor Perez.\n\tThe Zerahite clan, named after their
        ancestor Zerah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the subclans descended from the Perezites:\n\tThe Hezronites,
        named after their ancestor Hezron.\n\tThe Hamulites, named after their ancestor
        Hamul.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Judah. Their registered troops numbered 76,500.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Issachar
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Issachar:\n\tThe
        Tolaite clan, named after their ancestor Tola.\n\tThe Puite clan, named after
        their ancestor Puah.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:23 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Samaritan Pentateuch, Greek and Syriac versions, and Latin Vulgate
            (see also 1 Chr 7:1); Hebrew reads '
          body: The Punite clan, named after its ancestor Puvah.
    - title: 
      content: "The Jashubite clan, named after their ancestor Jashub.\n\tThe Shimronite
        clan, named after their ancestor Shimron.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Issachar. Their registered troops numbered
        64,300.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Zebulun
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Zebulun:\n\tThe Seredite
        clan, named after their ancestor Sered.\n\tThe Elonite clan, named after
        their ancestor Elon.\n\tThe Jahleelite clan, named after their ancestor Jahleel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Zebulun. Their registered troops numbered
        60,500.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Manasseh
      content: 'Two clans were descended from Joseph through Manasseh and Ephraim.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the clans descended from Manasseh:\n\tThe Makirite clan,
        named after their ancestor Makir.\n\tThe Gileadite clan, named after their
        ancestor Gilead, Makir\u2019s son.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the subclans descended from the Gileadites:\n\tThe Iezerites,
        named after their ancestor Iezer.\n\tThe Helekites, named after their ancestor
        Helek.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Asrielites, named after their ancestor Asriel.\n\tThe Shechemites,
        named after their ancestor Shechem.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Shemidaites, named after their ancestor Shemida.\n\tThe Hepherites,
        named after their ancestor Hepher.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "(One of Hepher\u2019s descendants, Zelophehad, had no sons, but his
        daughters\u2019 names were Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Manasseh. Their registered troops numbered
        52,700.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Ephraim
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Ephraim:\n\tThe Shuthelahite
        clan, named after their ancestor Shuthelah.\n\tThe Bekerite clan, named after
        their ancestor Beker.\n\tThe Tahanite clan, named after their ancestor Tahan.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This was the subclan descended from the Shuthelahites:\n\tThe Eranites,
        named after their ancestor Eran.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the clans of Ephraim. Their registered troops numbered
        32,500.\n\tThese clans of Manasseh and Ephraim were all descendants of Joseph.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Benjamin
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Benjamin:\n\tThe
        Belaite clan, named after their ancestor Bela.\n\tThe Ashbelite clan, named
        after their ancestor Ashbel.\n\tThe Ahiramite clan, named after their ancestor
        Ahiram.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Shuphamite clan, named after their ancestor Shupham.[COMMENT[0]]The
        Huphamite clan, named after their ancestor Hupham.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:39 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in some Hebrew manuscripts, Samaritan Pentateuch, Greek and Syriac
            versions, and Latin Vulgate; most Hebrew manuscripts read '
          body: Shephupham.
    - title: 
      content: "These were the subclans descended from the Belaites:\n\tThe Ardites,
        named after their ancestor Ard.[COMMENT[0]]The Naamites, named after their
        ancestor Naaman.  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:40 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Samaritan Pentateuch, some Greek manuscripts, and Latin Vulgate;
            Hebrew lacks '
          body: named after their ancestor Ard.
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Benjamin. Their registered troops numbered
        45,600.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Dan
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Dan:\n\tThe Shuhamite
        clan, named after their ancestor Shuham.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the Shuhamite clans of Dan. Their registered troops numbered
        64,400.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Asher
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Asher:\n\tThe Imnite
        clan, named after their ancestor Imnah.\n\tThe Ishvite clan, named after
        their ancestor Ishvi.\n\tThe Beriite clan, named after their ancestor Beriah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the subclans descended from the Beriites:\n\tThe Heberites,
        named after their ancestor Heber.\n\tThe Malkielites, named after their ancestor
        Malkiel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Asher also had a daughter named Serah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Asher. Their registered troops numbered 53,400.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Naphtali
      content: "These were the clans descended from the sons of Naphtali:\n\tThe
        Jahzeelite clan, named after their ancestor Jahzeel.\n\tThe Gunite clan,
        named after their ancestor Guni.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Jezerite clan, named after their ancestor Jezer.\n\tThe Shillemite
        clan, named after their ancestor Shillem.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the clans of Naphtali. Their registered troops numbered
        45,400.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Results of the Registration
      content: 'In summary, the registered troops of all Israel numbered 601,730.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDivide the land among the tribes, and distribute the grants
        of land in proportion to the tribes\u2019 populations, as indicated by the
        number of names on the list. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Give the larger tribes more land and the smaller tribes less land,
        each group receiving a grant in proportion to the size of its population. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But you must assign the land by lot, and give land to each ancestral
        tribe according to the number of names on the list. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Each grant of land must be assigned by lot among the larger and smaller
        tribal groups.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Tribe of Levi
      content: "This is the record of the Levites who were counted according to their
        clans:\n\tThe Gershonite clan, named after their ancestor Gershon.\n\tThe
        Kohathite clan, named after their ancestor Kohath.\n\tThe Merarite clan,
        named after their ancestor Merari.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Libnites, the Hebronites, the Mahlites, the Mushites, and the
        Korahites were all subclans of the Levites.\n\tNow Kohath was the ancestor
        of Amram, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and Amram\u2019s wife was named Jochebed. She also was a descendant
        of Levi, born among the Levites in the land of Egypt. Amram and Jochebed
        became the parents of Aaron, Moses, and their sister, Miriam. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'To Aaron were born Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Nadab and Abihu died when they burned before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        the wrong kind of fire, different than he had commanded.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The men from the Levite clans who were one month old or older numbered
        23,000. But the Levites were not included in the registration of the rest
        of the people of Israel because they were not given an allotment of land
        when it was divided among the Israelites.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So these are the results of the registration of the people of Israel
        as conducted by Moses and Eleazar the priest on the plains of Moab beside
        the Jordan River, across from Jericho. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Not one person on this list had been among those listed in the previous
        registration taken by Moses and Aaron in the wilderness of Sinai. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said of them, \u201CThey
        will all die in the wilderness.\u201D Not one of them survived except Caleb
        son of Jephunneh and Joshua son of Nun."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Daughters of Zelophehad
      content: "One day a petition was presented by the daughters of Zelophehad\u2014Mahlah,
        Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah. Their father, Zelophehad, was a descendant
        of Hepher son of Gilead, son of Makir, son of Manasseh, son of Joseph. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These women stood before Moses, Eleazar the priest, the tribal leaders,
        and the entire community at the entrance of the Tabernacle.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the Tent of Meeting.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COur father died in the wilderness,\u201D they said. \u201CHe
        was not among Korah\u2019s followers, who rebelled against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t;
        he died because of his own sin. But he had no sons. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why should the name of our father disappear from his clan just because
        he had no sons? Give us property along with the rest of our relatives.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses brought their case before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe claim of the daughters of Zelophehad is legitimate. You
        must give them a grant of land along with their father\u2019s relatives.
        Assign them the property that would have been given to their father.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd give the following instructions to the people of Israel:
        If a man dies and has no son, then give his inheritance to his daughters. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And if he has no daughter either, transfer his inheritance to his
        brothers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If he has no brothers, give his inheritance to his father\u2019s
        brothers. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if his father has no brothers, give his inheritance to the nearest
        relative in his clan. This is a legal requirement for the people of Israel,
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded Moses.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Joshua Chosen to Lead Israel
      content: "One day the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CClimb
        one of the mountains east of the river,[COMMENT[0]] and look out over the
        land I have given the people of Israel. "
      comments:
      - number: '27:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: the mountains of Abarim.
    - title: 
      content: 'After you have seen it, you will die like your brother, Aaron, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "for you both rebelled against my instructions in the wilderness of
        Zin. When the people of Israel rebelled, you failed to demonstrate my holiness
        to them at the waters.\u201D (These are the waters of Meribah at Kadesh[COMMENT[0]]
        in the wilderness of Zin.)  "
      comments:
      - number: '27:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: waters of Meribath-kadesh.
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses said to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, you are the God who gives
        breath to all creatures. Please appoint a new man as leader for the community. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Give them someone who will guide them wherever they go and will lead
        them into battle, so the community of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will
        not be like sheep without a shepherd.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CTake Joshua son of
        Nun, who has the Spirit in him, and lay your hands on him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Present him to Eleazar the priest before the whole community, and
        publicly commission him to lead the people. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Transfer some of your authority to him so the whole community of
        Israel will obey him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When direction from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is needed, Joshua
        will stand before Eleazar the priest, who will use the Urim\u2014one of the
        sacred lots cast before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2014to determine
        his will. This is how Joshua and the rest of the community of Israel will
        determine everything they should do.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses did as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded. He presented
        Joshua to Eleazar the priest and the whole community. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Moses laid his hands on him and commissioned him to lead the people,
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded through Moses.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Daily Offerings
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGive these instructions to the people of Israel: The offerings
        you present as special gifts are a pleasing aroma to me; they are my food.
        See to it that they are brought at the appointed times and offered according
        to my instructions.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSay to the people: This is the special gift you must present
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as your daily burnt offering. You must
        offer two one-year-old male lambs with no defects. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Sacrifice one lamb in the morning and the other in the evening. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'With each lamb you must offer a grain offering of two quarts[COMMENT[0]]
        of choice flour mixed with one quart[COMMENT[1]] of pure oil of pressed olives. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:5a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '1/10 of an ephah '
        - ft: '[2.2 liters]; also in 28:13, 21, 29.'
          body: 
      - number: '28:5b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '1/4 of a hin '
        - ft: '[1 liter]; also in 28:7.'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "This is the regular burnt offering instituted at Mount Sinai as a
        special gift, a pleasing aroma to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Along with it you must present the proper liquid offering of one
        quart of alcoholic drink with each lamb, poured out in the Holy Place as
        an offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Offer the second lamb in the evening with the same grain offering
        and liquid offering. It, too, is a special gift, a pleasing aroma to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Sabbath Offerings
      content: "\u201COn the Sabbath day, sacrifice two one-year-old male lambs with
        no defects. They must be accompanied by a grain offering of four quarts[COMMENT[0]]
        of choice flour moistened with olive oil, and a liquid offering. "
      comments:
      - number: '28:9 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '2/10 of an ephah '
        - ft: '[4.4 liters]; also in 28:12, 20, 28.'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'This is the burnt offering to be presented each Sabbath day, in addition
        to the regular burnt offering and its accompanying liquid offering.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Monthly Offerings
      content: "\u201COn the first day of each month, present an extra burnt offering
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of two young bulls, one ram, and seven
        one-year-old male lambs, all with no defects. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These must be accompanied by grain offerings of choice flour moistened
        with olive oil\u2014six quarts[COMMENT[0]] with each bull, four quarts with
        the ram, "
      comments:
      - number: '28:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '3/10 of an ephah '
        - ft: '[6.6 liters]; also in 28:20, 28.'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "and two quarts with each lamb. This burnt offering will be a special
        gift, a pleasing aroma to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You must also present a liquid offering with each sacrifice: two
        quarts[COMMENT[0]] of wine for each bull, a third of a gallon[COMMENT[1]]
        for the ram, and one quart[COMMENT[2]] for each lamb. Present this monthly
        burnt offering on the first day of each month throughout the year.  '
      comments:
      - number: '28:14a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '1/2 of a hin '
        - ft: '[2 liters].'
          body: 
      - number: '28:14b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '1/3 of a hin '
        - ft: '[1.3 liters].'
          body: 
      - number: '28:14c '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '1/4 of a hin '
        - ft: '[1 liter].'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COn the first day of each month, you must also offer one male
        goat for a sin offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. This is in
        addition to the regular burnt offering and its accompanying liquid offering.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Offerings for the Passover
      content: "\u201COn the fourteenth day of the first month,[COMMENT[0]] you must
        celebrate the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s Passover. "
      comments:
      - number: '28:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: This day in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in late March,
            April, or early May.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "On the following day\u2014the fifteenth day of the month\u2014a joyous,
        seven-day festival will begin, but no bread made with yeast may be eaten. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The first day of the festival will be an official day for holy assembly,
        and no ordinary work may be done on that day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As a special gift you must present a burnt offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2014two
        young bulls, one ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs, all with no defects. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These will be accompanied by grain offerings of choice flour moistened
        with olive oil\u2014six quarts with each bull, four quarts with the ram, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and two quarts with each of the seven lambs. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You must also offer a male goat as a sin offering to purify yourselves
        and make yourselves right with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '28:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'to make atonement for yourselves; '
        - ft: also in 28:30.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Present these offerings in addition to your regular morning burnt
        offering. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On each of the seven days of the festival, this is how you must prepare
        the food offering that is presented as a special gift, a pleasing aroma to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. These will be offered in addition to
        the regular burnt offerings and liquid offerings. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The seventh day of the festival will be another official day for
        holy assembly, and no ordinary work may be done on that day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Offerings for the Festival of Harvest
      content: "\u201CAt the Festival of Harvest,[COMMENT[0]] when you present the
        first of your new grain to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, you must
        call an official day for holy assembly, and you may do no ordinary work on
        that day. "
      comments:
      - number: '28:26 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'Festival of Weeks. '
        - ft: This was later called the Festival of Pentecost (see Acts 2:1). It
            is celebrated today as Shavuot (or Shabuoth).
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Present a special burnt offering on that day as a pleasing aroma
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t. It will consist of two young bulls,
